WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.120
My name is Stephanie Butland. I'm a biologist and

00:00:04.800 --> 00:00:10.360
Some of us already know each other from my prior role as our open size first community manager

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:17.600
I work now with Julie Lowndes at OpenScapes where we use the Kyber package to do what he said it does.

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:22.139
I remember how powerful I felt the first time I used Kyber to make a

00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:28.280
multi-page Google Doc Agenda and a website on GitHub with just a couple of lines of code and I want to share some of

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:30.040
this with you now.

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:32.040
But first a bit about OpenScapes.

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:36.639
OpenScapes is about growing the open science movement and sharing some of this great vibe

00:00:36.639 --> 00:00:44.040
we hear at PositConf with the research teams we work with at NASA, NOAA Fisheries, and Fred Hutch Cancer Center here in Seattle.

00:00:44.919 --> 00:00:51.639
We work with research teams to help them do better science in less time together and this involves both tooling and people.

00:00:52.639 --> 00:00:58.599
Our champions program is a multi-month open data science mentorship program for science teams.

00:00:58.639 --> 00:01:03.240
This requires a whole lot of teaching, but it also requires creating a lot of infrastructure.

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:12.099
One fall we led four concurrent cohorts with 160 government scientists. This required me to create four different GitHub repos,

00:01:13.239 --> 00:01:18.239
160 markdown files so that everyone could work in their own file in the GitHub clinic,

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:20.720
20 different Google Doc Agendas, and

00:01:21.559 --> 00:01:23.559
160 completion certificates.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:31.599
This work when done manually is error prone, it's time-consuming, the effort involved is grossly underestimated, and it's unseen.

00:01:33.279 --> 00:01:38.160
Kyber package replaces manual steps with R functions and was driven by the question

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:41.680
how much automation can we drive with minimal coding for the end-user?

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:47.279
It's inherently powerful to design around commonly used and widely understood tools.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:52.760
So why can't we just do things with a spreadsheet, an R script, and a friendly front door?

00:01:53.279 --> 00:02:00.199
Speaking of friendly front doors, Kyber was developed by Sean Cross who is a hero in the R community.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:05.599
He was there in the first OpenScapes champions cohort back in 2019 when he got to see

00:02:06.279 --> 00:02:09.320
firsthand the manual effort involved in putting this infrastructure together.

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:16.039
He developed Kyber in collaboration with Julie Lowndes, OpenScapes founding director, and now Andy Tuescher and

00:02:16.479 --> 00:02:20.080
Anna Holder and Nick Tierney and I have all contributed to Kyber in different ways.

00:02:21.080 --> 00:02:25.600
So I'll give you one use case, creating an agenda for one of our cohort calls.

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:31.360
Every agenda has the same basic structure and we use Kyber to make us agenda sandwiches

00:02:31.839 --> 00:02:37.479
from a variety of different recipes and our well-stocked R markdown refrigerator of content.

00:02:38.479 --> 00:02:42.839
We put all the metadata for individual cohorts in a Google Sheet.

00:02:42.839 --> 00:02:48.520
So there's the cohort name, a start date, end date, and we put all of the content in

00:02:48.919 --> 00:02:53.800
markdown files as the content that goes into the agendas. In our markdown files, they live on GitHub,

00:02:54.039 --> 00:02:56.479
but they're indexed in the same spreadsheet.

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:04.360
With a single call from Kyber, I give input that is the registry, the URL of the

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:09.600
Google Sheet, the unique cohort name, and the call number of the agenda I want to create.

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:15.240
I take the output, I paste it into a Google Doc, and I have my multi-page agenda.

00:03:16.839 --> 00:03:22.520
So to use the GitHub analogy of forking, meaning reusing and extending a product,

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:28.440
other groups are forking OpenScapes teaching infrastructure using Kyber now, and they're forking the whole

00:03:28.679 --> 00:03:31.360
OpenScapes approach to meet their own organization's needs.

00:03:31.759 --> 00:03:35.000
Anna Holder's team at the California Waterboards are doing just this.

00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:40.160
They're the first organization to fork OpenScapes and independently lead these cohorts.

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:45.000
Through working with Anna, by co-working and screen sharing

00:03:45.639 --> 00:03:50.039
with Anna and her team, we've helped them add their own custom content into Kyber,

00:03:50.039 --> 00:03:57.679
so they create their own agendas and their repos and their completion certificates. And just last week, they kicked off their fourth

00:03:58.399 --> 00:04:00.559
independently-led OpenScapes champions cohort.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:05.479
Anna says, our ability to scale is directly related to Kyber.

00:04:05.960 --> 00:04:12.000
Instead of Anna doing all this copying and pasting, she gets to spend her time working directly with her colleagues,

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:14.520
helping them get unstuck in their workflows.

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:17.359
This has been my experience as well,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.720
and this was the original intent of Kyber in the first place.

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:24.920
And so we're really excited to see what the possibilities are

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:31.079
using this tool and having this great combination of tooling and people, and let's see what we can enable together.

00:04:31.359 --> 00:04:34.279
Thank you.

